dismissalText.commentary: Harry Tector b Ebadot Hossain 140 (113b 7x4 10x6 168m) SR: 123.89

dismissalComment.html: Tector misses the bash over long-on and bails fly. He walks back in disappointment, his parents applaud, his team-mates walk out to cheer him back. The crowd stand up and clap along as well, he raises his bat as Shipping up to Boston plays in the background. That was a full ball that curved in, Tector stayed leg side and looked to swing it golf-like over mid-on and Ebadot pointed his index finger towards the batter in celebration

dismissalComment.html: Appeal for caught behind turned down. Tamim asks, discusses and reviews. It's a fair ball, the question is whether Stirling got an inside edge. That was a length ball that came in again, Stirling tried to block it towards mid-off but the sharp movement had him try and check the shot. He was a bit too late, the ball took the inside edge. Clear spike on Ultra-Edge, and Mushfiqur leapt to the left to take a good catch. The fielders cheered as soon they saw the nick.

dismissalText.commentary: Curtis Campher lbw b Taijul Islam 8 (11b 0x4 0x6 25m) SR: 72.72

dismissalComment.html: Huge lbw shout, given. Ireland review. Campher went across and tried to sweep the back-of-length ball. The leg stump was fully visible as he played the shot. Ultra-Edge is taking some time to load. It shows no contact with the bat. Campher was on one knee right in front of middle and off. Ball hit over the knee-roll of the front pad and Hawk-Eye shows three reds. Cheers from the crowd, Campher walks back

commentPreTextItems.html: Free hit. And Mushfiqur is on strike, too. Four balls, four runs needed. The field won't change since it is the same batter on strike.

commentTextItems.html: And Mushfiqur does it for Bangladesh! Makes that life count. Glimmer of hope is enough for the veteran. Gets across off and ramps the length ball well over the wicketkeeper's head. Joy in the Bangladesh camp, not so in the Irish camp.

commentPostTextItems.html: Bangladesh take a 1-0 lead but both teams continued to breathe life into the ODI format and entertained a vociferous crowd in Chelmsford. The game was curtailed and it went overtime but delivered top-quality cricket that signal exciting times ahead. We'll do this all over again in a couple of days, see you then. Goodbye for now from me, Ekanth, my co-commentator, S Sudarshanan, and our scorers, Binoy George and Chandan Duorah.

Najmul Hossain Shanto, POTM: I feel very happy, it was nice. I think Hridoy batted well. His intent helped me. It's pretty cold but we can't control conditions. We just focus on our game. We didn't feel we were outside Bangladesh, thanks to the crowd. Hopefully they can come in the next match as well. He later thanks the crowd for coming in Bangla, his native tongue.

Tamim Iqbal, Bangladesh Captain: The support is unbelievable when we played in England. I remember our crowd outnumbered England in 2017, it's special. Due to the ground dimensions and the wicket, we thought it was chaseable. It's not a ground where you need to look for a boundary all the time, they will come. Kudos to Shanto. If Towhid keeps performing the way he does, he will be gold.

Andy Balbirnie, Ireland Captain: Hard one to pinpoint, will sit down tomorrow and look at it. It's a tough ground to defend, credit to them for the chase. We can take a lot of confidence. When you have a good score, you're in the game. Can't fault batters. Shoutout to Tector. I wouldn't look too much into him making tons in losing causes. He'll score more in wins. Bangladesh have a great team. We were good but not enough. We entertained the crowd, hope to do it on Sunday.
nzbsz: "10 points and Bangladesh moved to the third position in the point table. Another 10 won't change it much but the morale will be high. "

8:50pm And so, a long, never-ending match has finished in a thriller! And it was down to the experienced Mushfiqur to get them over the line. It never seemed as if his heroics would be needed when Shanto was going out all guns blazing along with Hridoy. The pair never let the required run rate go out of hand and kept Bangladesh in the game. But once they both fell - with Shanto having scored a fantastic, maiden ODI ton - the game was open. Ireland squeezed in some economical overs and took it to the last over. Adair almost did it by dismissing Mushfiqur, only for it to be a waist-high no-ball. And rest, as they say, is history. Bangladesh are 1-0 up with a game to go. Presentations soon.
Shovik: "I'm loving Mushfiqur in this finisher's role. A few heartbreaks in the past have moulded him into a commendable finisher, really clinical. "
